it complies with requirements of the FCRA (15 USC 1681).  There have been  recent amendments with this federal law which would lead most readers  of the Act to the conclusion that a separate independent disclosure is necessary, however, it is clear that is not necessary.  Section 604(b)(2) of the Act requires that a \"clear and conspicuous\" disclosure be made in writing to the applicant \"in a document that consists solely of the disclosure, that a consumer report may be obtained for employment purposes.\"  Under this subsection, if we would use a consumer report (i.e., a credit report) for an employment purpose (hire, fire, promote, demote), we would need to provide a separate disclosure.  This paper would also need to contain a description of the grievance procedure in the event of an adverse action.  In the event that a credit report would be used to support an \"adverse action\" such as not hiring, even where there was no purely negative information on the report, the applicant would need to be provided a copy of the report, and a certain \"description of rights\" set forth in the Act in Section 609(c)(3).\r\n\r\nHowever an exclusion exists in the Act as to new hires.  Section 603(d)(2)(D) states that a \"consumer report\" is not a communication between an employer and a credit reporting agency if it is used for new hire purposes and the applicant consents \"orally or in writing\" before the communication.  Therefore, the Town\'s current application-- and even just an oral \"OK\" from the applicant-- would suffice to be covered as an exclusion under the act, and therefore not require a separate disclosure.  \r\n\r\nHowever, in the event that a personnel action is taken from a \"credit report\" after a new hire, then the Section 604 & 609 disclosures and grievance procedures would be required.\r\n\r\nI have enclosed some documents for your review, including the highlighted sections of the Act.  Please let me know if you have any questions.','','',NULL,NULL,'','2